an actual economy?

00:10:17.120 --> 00:10:19.399
Student:  IPOs.
 

00:10:19.399 --> 00:10:21.750
Prof: IPOs are a big way
to do it.

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:26.129
In general, the joint stock
corporation is a way to do it.

00:10:26.129 --> 00:10:27.720
How do banks aggregate capital?
 

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:29.360
Student:  Deposits.
 

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:37.500
Prof: Thousands of
little deposits make big funds.

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:43.927
Okay, so we're getting there
with capital and what I want to

00:10:43.927 --> 00:10:49.809
do now is continue the
agricultural theme and see if we

00:10:49.809 --> 00:10:55.802
can relate what we're talking
about to the generation of

00:10:55.802 --> 00:10:59.179
actual wealth in society.
 

00:10:59.179 --> 00:11:04.090
This is called a seed drill.
 

00:11:04.090 --> 00:11:09.057
It is a way of planting
millions of seeds in a very

00:11:09.057 --> 00:11:13.629
systematic, precise,
and cost effective way.

00:11:13.629 --> 00:11:18.610
One characteristic feature of
how capital works is combining

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:23.254
different factors in the
production of the same thing in

00:11:23.254 --> 00:11:26.038
an extremely intelligent way.
 

00:11:26.038 --> 00:11:30.535
A way that represents the
accumulated experience of

00:11:30.535 --> 00:11:36.110
society and when you do it well
you succeed, and when you do it

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:37.908
poorly you fail.
 

00:11:37.908 --> 00:11:41.182
You can actually fail even when
you do it well,

00:11:41.182 --> 00:11:45.450
but you're very unlikely to
succeed when you do it poorly.

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:51.678
Now here I want to compare two
very similar technologies,

00:11:51.678 --> 00:11:59.672
