00:35:33.601 --> 00:35:34.869
Nations?
 

00:35:34.869 --> 00:35:37.989
Okay, the rest of you are in
for a treat.

00:35:37.989 --> 00:35:42.369
Smith is not only a great
writer but a great thinker.

00:35:42.369 --> 00:35:47.351
He is a much more complex
thinker than we usually imagine

00:35:47.351 --> 00:35:48.420
him to be.
 

00:35:48.420 --> 00:35:55.916
He was not a believer that it's
just fine for the poor to starve

00:35:55.916 --> 00:35:57.940
in the streets.
 

00:35:57.940 --> 00:36:00.972
He actually had very
complicated news about that

00:36:00.972 --> 00:36:04.909
which are broadly analogous to
the philosopher John Rawls,

00:36:04.909 --> 00:36:10.063
and Rawls' difference principle
about what inequalities are

00:36:10.063 --> 00:36:11.992
justified,
namely those which

00:36:11.992 --> 00:36:13.110
&gt;
 

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:18.182
ultimately in some way to the
benefit of the least favored

00:36:18.182 --> 00:36:20.320
stratum in an economy.
 

00:36:20.320 --> 00:36:24.746
The Manifesto,
already mentioned,

00:36:24.746 --> 00:36:31.250
and in both cases we'll leave
out a good bit.

00:36:31.250 --> 00:36:33.518
Smith is a very old book.
 

00:36:33.518 --> 00:36:36.539
I recommend to you the Bantam
paperback,

00:36:36.539 --> 00:36:43.592
$7.95 of Smith because it has
wonderful little summaries of

00:36:43.592 --> 00:36:50.280
each paragraph in italics which
allow speed reading,

00:36:50.280 --> 00:36:55.148
which is actually a very useful
thing when a book would take a

00:36:55.148 --> 00:36:58.659
week to plow through in a
careful reading.

00:36:58.659 --> 00:37:02.047
We'll focus on just three or
four points there,

00:37:02.047 --> 00:37:05.878
three or four arguments in
Smith, but they are really

00:37:05.878 --> 00:37:08.530
powerful and important readings.
 

00:37:08.530 --> 00:37:12.349
The Constitution of
Liberty is by F.A.

00:37:12.349 --> 00:37:15.820
Hayek and we'll just read two
chapters that will be in a

00:37:15.820 --> 00:37:17.650
packet, which you will get.
 

00:37:17.650 --> 00:37:25.246
Hayek is the arch-conservative,
a market conservative from whom

00:37:25.246 --> 00:37:29.780
most of the conservative
movement--

00:37:29.780 --> 00:37:32.000
not not concerned with social
authority--

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:37.971
but the libertarian side of
American conservatism relies

00:37:37.971 --> 00:37:41.329
primarily on Hayek,
actually.

00:37:41.329 --> 00:37:47.835
Farewell to Alms,
this book, by a guy named

00:37:47.835 --> 00:37:52.481
Gregory Clarke,
is a book which says

00:37:52.481 --> 00:37:57.969
capitalism: more and better;
pour it on.

00:37:57.969 --> 00:38:03.010
As capitalism increases its
reach the world will grow

00:38:03.010 --> 00:38:05.239
wealthier and better.
 

00:38:05.239 --> 00:38:09.590
It is a polemical work,
written by an economist,

00:38:09.590 --> 00:38:13.416
and you will find things to
argue with even if you more or

00:38:13.416 --> 00:38:17.309
less agree with him you will
find many things to argue with

00:38:17.309 --> 00:38:21.539
him about and that will be an
important book in the course.

00:38:21.539 --> 00:38:27.333
The Mystery of Capital
by Hernando DeSoto is an

00:38:27.333 --> 00:38:33.784
argument about why the less
developed countries in the world

00:38:33.784 --> 00:38:38.744
are less developed,
and the gist of it is that

00:38:38.744 --> 00:38:44.043
formal and enforceable property
rights are a precondition to

00:38:44.043 --> 00:38:46.110
capital development.
 

00:38:46.110 --> 00:38:51.940
It's a very powerful piece of
work.

00:38:51.940 --> 00:38:55.742
Richard Posner,
The Failure of

00:38:55.742 --> 00:39:01.208
Capitalism,
Posner--anybody know who Posner

00:39:01.208 --> 00:39:02.039
is?
 

00:39:02.039 --> 00:39:05.840
Tell us loud and clear.
 

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:07.090
Student:  A judge.
 

00:39:07.090 --> 00:39:10.059
Prof: He's a judge and
he's a judge of what persuasion,

00:39:10.059 --> 00:39:10.840
would you say?
 

00:39:10.840 --> 00:39:15.476
He's a very conservative judge,
teaches at The University of

00:39:15.476 --> 00:39:18.934
Chicago Law School,
and he has written a very

00:39:18.934 --> 00:39:22.630
penetrating analysis of the
current crisis.

00:39:22.630 --> 00:39:27.480
It is--I read maybe 20 books
and picked one on this subject,

00:39:27.480 --> 00:39:34.070
and this is the clearest and
most honest,

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:37.092
I think, and he doesn't--he
does no ideological distortion

00:39:37.092 --> 00:39:38.420
here that I can detect.
 

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:44.090
It is just a penetrating and
straightforward analysis of what

00:39:44.090 --> 00:39:48.250
happened, and for that reason
very useful.

00:39:48.250 --> 00:39:52.889
The Bottom Billion by
Paul Collier,

00:39:52.889 --> 00:39:57.110
who is a World Bank economist
who teaches at Oxford,

00:39:57.110 --> 00:40:02.807
and in this maps out a
diagnosis and a strategy for

00:40:02.807 --> 00:40:09.532
using market mechanisms and
capital development to alleviate

00:40:09.532 --> 00:40:13.179
most of the world's poverty.
 

00:40:13.179 --> 00:40:18.483
Finally, The White
Tiger, this is fiction,

00:40:18.483 --> 00:40:24.561
but there are times when
fiction is better at describing

00:40:24.561 --> 00:40:28.429
the real world than nonfiction.
 

00:40:28.429 --> 00:40:35.775
This is a brutally penetrating
novel written from the point of

00:40:35.775 --> 00:40:41.554
view of a very poor,
very smart, and in many ways

00:40:41.554 --> 00:40:45.889
flawed young man in South India.
 

00:40:45.889 --> 00:40:50.530
It won the Man Booker prize
last year for fiction.

00:40:50.530 --> 00:40:56.617
It is, for our age,
it is as good as Dickens and

00:40:56.617 --> 00:41:01.670
Zola were for the nineteenth
century.

00:41:01.670 --> 00:41:03.820
It's just a brilliant book.
 

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:04.780
I couldn't put it down.
 

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:09.288
Ten people told me I had to
read it, and I kept shrugging my

00:41:09.288 --> 00:41:13.719
shoulders and that's when I
started, and I read it front to

00:41:13.719 --> 00:41:15.630
back in one long day.
 

00:41:15.630 --> 00:41:20.201
It is--if you want to
understand why there are a

00:41:20.201 --> 00:41:25.842
billion or two billion people
out there for whom capitalism

00:41:25.842 --> 00:41:31.385
looks not like a powerful
mechanism of production but like

00:41:31.385 --> 00:41:34.789
an extremely coercive system.
 

00:41:34.789 --> 00:41:41.219
The White Tiger is a
great way to do that.

00:41:41.219 --> 00:41:44.842
Chris Buckley's,
Thank You For Smoking,

00:41:44.842 --> 00:41:45.969
is optional.
 

00:41:45.969 --> 00:41:50.231
We will also use the case
method and the case method

00:41:50.231 --> 00:41:53.489
occupies about a third of the
course.

00:41:53.489 --> 00:41:59.487
We will use--the ones in white
are straightforward cases,

00:41:59.487 --> 00:42:05.913
the ones in gold we'll have the
people in the room or some of

00:42:05.913 --> 00:42:07.518
the people.
 

00:42:07.518 --> 00:42:14.067
Polaroid is the story of the
land camera and a brilliant

00:42:14.067 --> 00:42:20.018
technology which ultimately
crashed and burned,

00:42:20.018 --> 00:42:24.717
and it's--the case is a hard
business school case about the

00:42:24.717 --> 00:42:29.416
attempt to get that business
through its crisis at the time

00:42:29.416 --> 00:42:31.280
that it went broke.
 

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:37.268
Goldman Sachs IPO
terrifically--it's a good HBS

00:42:37.268 --> 00:42:41.036
case,
and better yet we'll have Paolo

00:42:41.036 --> 00:42:45.876
Zannoni with us to tell the
story from the inside of the

00:42:45.876 --> 00:42:47.460
Goldman system.
 

00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:53.925
Wanda Rapaczynski is the story
of getting a business going in

00:42:53.925 --> 00:42:58.559
Poland just after the death of
communism.

00:42:58.559 --> 00:43:04.934
A Yale-trained business woman
who created something called

00:43:04.934 --> 00:43:08.376
Agora S.A.,
which is the largest publishing

00:43:08.376 --> 00:43:13.253
company in East Europe,
and how she coped with the

00:43:13.253 --> 00:43:18.003
toxic environment,
the toxic business environment,

00:43:18.003 --> 00:43:19.679
left over by communism.
 

00:43:19.679 --> 00:43:25.010
Selco India is a microfinance
story.

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:31.197
Cardiothoracic Systems is a
tech story and I'm going to have

00:43:31.197 --> 00:43:37.699
the Dean of SOM come and do it
as a business case with you,

00:43:37.699 --> 00:43:40.139
which means you're going to
need to wear helmets.

00:43:40.139 --> 00:43:43.018
She is an aggressive cold
caller.

00:43:43.018 --> 00:43:48.121
By the way, I'm going to make
two kinds of calls in this

00:43:48.121 --> 00:43:50.590
course,
cold calls are the kind of

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:53.260
thing I did today where you get
no warning,

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:59.289
and warm calls I'll send you an
email and say heads up about,

00:43:59.289 --> 00:44:05.217
and in the second case you've
really got to have something to

00:44:05.217 --> 00:44:05.809
say.
 

00:44:05.809 --> 00:44:12.545
Some of the fun in this stuff
is the back and forth between

00:44:12.545 --> 00:44:16.030
you and me, and you and you.
 

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:21.329
The Enron case,
Jim Alexander is an important

00:44:21.329 --> 00:44:23.860
guy in this course.
 

00:44:23.860 --> 00:44:25.889
Jim would you just stand up and
wave?

00:44:25.889 --> 00:44:32.143
Jim was--Jim is a good friend
of mine who had a career in

00:44:32.143 --> 00:44:36.610
investment banking and then at
Enron,

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:41.139
and he was Chief Financial
Officer of Enron,

00:44:41.139 --> 00:44:45.391
Global Pipeline &amp; Power,
and he saw what was happening

00:44:45.391 --> 00:44:46.809
and got out.
 

00:44:46.809 --> 00:44:52.958
He is referred to as the fly in
the ointment in Smartest Guys

00:44:52.958 --> 00:44:57.449
in the Room,
which is the popularized story

00:44:57.449 --> 00:44:59.500
of Enron's crash.
 

00:44:59.500 --> 00:45:04.177
He then went on and co-founded
Spinnaker Exploration whose

00:45:04.177 --> 00:45:08.527
operating principle was:
think what Enron would do and

00:45:08.527 --> 00:45:10.170
do the opposite.
 

00:45:10.170 --> 00:45:17.597
Spinnaker became a public
company and was extremely

00:45:17.597 --> 00:45:19.530
successful.
 

00:45:19.530 --> 00:45:22.704
Medley Global Advisors,
this is a case about gathering

00:45:22.704 --> 00:45:25.940
business intelligence and
selling it at high prices.

00:45:25.940 --> 00:45:30.429
Medley is another Yale-trained
person.

00:45:30.429 --> 00:45:34.927
He founded the company and the
case is about his attempt to

00:45:34.927 --> 00:45:37.911
sell the company,
which he did,

00:45:37.911 --> 00:45:41.550
so he's selling a company
that--

00:45:41.550 --> 00:45:47.088
which is posthumously his,
and he actually sold it for

00:45:47.088 --> 00:45:52.643
fifty seven million bucks,
and it's a no venture medley

00:45:52.643 --> 00:45:56.159
story and he's a very
interesting guy.

00:45:56.159 --> 00:46:00.280
Then maybe we'll talk about
Mory's.

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:04.559
I'm chair of a workout
committee which is trying to put

00:46:04.559 --> 00:46:08.838
more effective business and it
turns out to be a really

00:46:08.838 --> 00:46:10.900
interesting hard case.
 

